[/quote]

And even more useless - maybe ask jagex
The only really irreversible thing it can do is identifier obfuscation, which can be attributed more to its irreversible nature than to the “advanced” techniques Zelix uses.

[quote=“moparisthebest, post:17, topic:2761”]I found this rather interesting:

http://today.java.net/pub/a/today/2004/10/22/obfuscation.html[/quote]
Nice basic introduction on this topic.
But I do not agree with the authors opinion on the advantage of this so called “overload induction”. IMHO it adds very little additional protection and I never had a real problem dealing with it. And loosing overload information is not a big deal because on encountering some of those methods subject to information loss while examining the code, you quickly realize they belong together if they really do! (due to same/similar logical structure etc…)

http://today.java.net/pub/a/today/2004/10/22/obfuscation.html
[/quote]

That’s a good article; it’s actually similar to the disabling right click argument…you can do it, but anyone who wants to see your code can. Same way here, portions such as encrypted string literals are quite easy to decrypt, as the keys and encryption method are provided right in the class. So yeah, in most cases, obfuscation isn’t really worth it.[/quote]

exactly, its like the article says, if somone wants your code they will get it no matter what, but if you put a few layers of security on there it will keep 99% of the population who doesnt have that kind of resolve out

item.title: Obfuscate
item.dc:creator: @Iamadam Iamadam
item.description:
@Iamadam wrote:

[quote=“moparisthebest, post:14, topic:2761”][quote author=BobDole81 link=topic=3039.msg29452#msg29452 date=1147562274]

Make it .exe, but its not that easy :\

Wrapping a java application into a jar file really doesn’t help to protect it…most wrappers basically compile it into an exe archive, which can be extracted by almost any archiving tool. Others just extract everything themselves into the temporary files…

Obfuscating (like ZKM does) helps to protect the code by encrypting strings, messing up the line numbers, and modify the control flow so that the code is less comprehensible after decompiling. There are free ones as well…yGuard, ProGuard…just google it.
[/quote]

if you use a program to actually compile java into native machine code such as JET or GCJ (?) there is no way you can decompile it to access the source correct?[/quote]

Correct, but often these programs dont work too well.

item.title: Obfuscate
item.dc:creator: @Krichevskoy Krichevskoy
item.description:
@Krichevskoy wrote:

en.wikipedia.org

Obfuscation (software)

In software development, obfuscation is the deliberate act of creating source or machine code that is difficult for humans to understand. Like obfuscation in natural language, it may use needlessly roundabout expressions to compose statements. Programmers may deliberately obfuscate code to conceal its purpose (security through obscurity) or its logic or implicit values embedded in it, primarily, in order to prevent tampering, deter reverse engineering, or even as a puzzle or recreational cha...


That should explain the concept that you’re trying to express.
As for actually obfuscating something, why? What are you writing that needs to be hidden?

item.dc:creator: @1337h4x 1337h4x
item.description:
@1337h4x wrote:

What does “obfuscate” mean?

This verb doesn't have a specific meaning related to computing, though it does seem to apply to a lot of computer jargon. It means "to deliberately make something unclear or difficult to understand, by making use of unfamiliar terminology". Which is precisely the reason why we have a Glossary on our web site. www.saol.com/glossary.asp
